"fabc\", \"cd\", \"dg\")`.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n**Input:** s = \"abababaccddb\"\n\n**Output:** 2\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nWe can partition the string `s` into 2 substrings like so: `(\"abab\", \"abaccddb\")`.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= s.length <= 1000`\n\n- `s` consists only of English lowercase letters.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-substring-partition-of-equal-character-frequency/","problemName":"Minimum Substring Partition of Equal Character Frequency","problemNumber":3144,"problemSlug":"minimum-substring-partition-of-equal-character-frequency","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":3144,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Array","Binary Search","Bit Manipulation"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"The **powerful array** of a non-negative integer `x` is defined as the shortest sorted array of powers of two that sum up to `x`. The table below illustrates examples of how the **powerful array** is determined. It can be proven that the powerful array of `x` is unique.\n\n| num | Binary Representation | powerful array |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| 1 | 00001 | [1] |\n| 8 | 01000 | [8] |\n| 10 | 01010 | [2, 8] |\n| 13 | 01101 | [1, 4, 8] |\n| 23 | 10111 | [1, 2, 4, 16] |\n\nThe array `big_nums` is created by concatenating the **powerful arrays** for every positive integer `i` in ascending order: 1, 2, 3, and so on. Thus, `big_nums` begins as `[1, 2, 1, 2, 4, 1, 4, 2, 4, 1, 2, 4, 8, ...]`.\n\nYou are given a 2D integer matrix `queries`, where for `queries[i] = [fromi, toi, modi]` you should calculate `(big_nums[fromi] * big_nums[fromi + 1] * ... * big_nums[toi]) % modi`.\n\nReturn an integer array `answer` such that `answer[i]` is the answer to the `i^(th)` query.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n**Input:** queries = [[1,3,7]]\n\n**Output:** [4]\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nThere is one query.\n\n`big_nums[1..3] = [2,1,2]`. The product of them is 4. The result is `4 % 7 = 4.`\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n**Input:** queries = [[2,5,3],[7,7,4]]\n\n**Output:** [2,2]\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nThere are two queries.\n\nFirst query: `big_nums[2..5] = [1,2,4,1]`. The product of them is 8. The result is `8 % 3 = 2`.\n\nSecond query: `big_nums[7] = 2`. The result is `2 % 4 = 2`.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= queries.length <= 500`\n\n- `queries[i].length == 3`\n\n- `0 <= queries[i][0] <= queries[i][1] <= 10¹⁵`\n\n- `1 <= queries[i][2] <= 10⁵`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array","Binary Search","Bit Manipulation"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Hard","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"The **powerful array** of a non-negative integer `x` is defined as the shortest sorted array of powers of two that sum up to `x`. The table below illustrates examples of how the **powerful array** is determined. It can be proven that the powerful array of `x` is unique.\n\n| num | Binary Representation | powerful array |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| 1 | 00001 | [1] |\n| 8 | 01000 | [8] |\n| 10 | 01010 | [2, 8] |\n| 13 | 01101 | [1, 4, 8] |\n| 23 | 10111 | [1, 2, 4, 16] |\n\nThe array `big_nums` is created by concatenating the **powerful arrays** for every positive integer `i` in ascending order: 1, 2, 3, and so on. Thus, `big_nums` begins as `[1, 2, 1, 2, 4, 1, 4, 2, 4, 1, 2, 4, 8, ...]`.\n\nYou are given a 2D integer matrix `queries`, where for `queries[i] = [fromi, toi, modi]` you should calculate `(big_nums[fromi] * big_nums[fromi + 1] * ... * big_nums[toi]) % modi`.\n\nReturn an integer array `answer` such that `answer[i]` is the answer to the `i^(th)` query.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n**Input:** queries = [[1,3,7]]\n\n**Output:** [4]\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nThere is one query.\n\n`big_nums[1..3] = [2,1,2]`. The product of them is 4. The result is `4 % 7 = 4.`\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n**Input:** queries = [[2,5,3],[7,7,4]]\n\n**Output:** [2,2]\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nThere are two queries.\n\nFirst query: `big_nums[2..5] = [1,2,4,1]`. The product of them is 8. The result is `8 % 3 = 2`.\n\nSecond query: `big_nums[7] = 2`. The result is `2 % 4 = 2`.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= queries.length <= 500`\n\n- `queries[i].length == 3`\n\n- `0 <= queries[i][0] <= queries[i][1] <= 10¹⁵`\n\n- `1 <= queries[i][2] <= 10⁵`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/find-products-of-elements-of-big-array/","problemName":"Find Products of Elements of Big Array","problemNumber":3145,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"The **powerful array** of a non-negative integer `x` is defined as the shortest sorted array of powers of two that sum up to `x`. The table below illustrates examples of how the **powerful array** is determined. It can be proven that the powerful array of `x` is unique.\n\n| num | Binary Representation | powerful array |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| 1 | 00001 | [1] |\n| 8 | 01000 | [8] |\n| 10 | 01010 | [2, 8] |\n| 13 | 01101 | [1, 4, 8] |\n| 23 | 10111 | [1, 2, 4, 16] |\n\nThe array `big_nums` is created by concatenating the **powerful arrays** for every positive integer `i` in ascending order: 1, 2, 3, and so on. Thus, `big_nums` begins as `[1, 2, 1, 2, 4, 1, 4, 2, 4, 1, 2, 4, 8, ...]`.\n\nYou are given a 2D integer matrix `queries`, where for `queries[i] = [fromi, toi, modi]` you should calculate `(big_nums[fromi] * big_nums[fromi + 1] * ... * big_nums[toi]) % modi`.\n\nReturn an integer array `answer` such that `answer[i]` is the answer to the `i^(th)` query.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n**Input:** queries = [[1,3,7]]\n\n**Output:** [4]\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nThere is one query.\n\n`big_nums[1..3] = [2,1,2]`. The product of them is 4. The result is `4 % 7 = 4.`\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n**Input:** queries = [[2,5,3],[7,7,4]]\n\n**Output:** [2,2]\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nThere are two queries.\n\nFirst query: `big_nums[2..5] = [1,2,4,1]`. The product of them is 8. The result is `8 % 3 = 2`.\n\nSecond query: `big_nums[7] = 2`. The result is `2 % 4 = 2`.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= queries.length <= 500`\n\n- `queries[i].length == 3`\n\n- `0 <= queries[i][0] <= queries[i][1] <= 10¹⁵`\n\n- `1 <= queries[i][2] <= 10⁵`","type":"text"}],"difficulty":"Hard","examples":[],"paidOnly":false,"problem":"The **powerful array** of a non-negative integer `x` is defined as the shortest sorted array of powers of two that sum up to `x`. The table below illustrates examples of how the **powerful array** is determined. It can be proven that the powerful array of `x` is unique.\n\n| num | Binary Representation | powerful array |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| 1 | 00001 | [1] |\n| 8 | 01000 | [8] |\n| 10 | 01010 | [2, 8] |\n| 13 | 01101 | [1, 4, 8] |\n| 23 | 10111 | [1, 2, 4, 16] |\n\nThe array `big_nums` is created by concatenating the **powerful arrays** for every positive integer `i` in ascending order: 1, 2, 3, and so on. Thus, `big_nums` begins as `[1, 2, 1, 2, 4, 1, 4, 2, 4, 1, 2, 4, 8, ...]`.\n\nYou are given a 2D integer matrix `queries`, where for `queries[i] = [fromi, toi, modi]` you should calculate `(big_nums[fromi] * big_nums[fromi + 1] * ... * big_nums[toi]) % modi`.\n\nReturn an integer array `answer` such that `answer[i]` is the answer to the `i^(th)` query.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n**Input:** queries = [[1,3,7]]\n\n**Output:** [4]\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nThere is one query.\n\n`big_nums[1..3] = [2,1,2]`. The product of them is 4. The result is `4 % 7 = 4.`\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n**Input:** queries = [[2,5,3],[7,7,4]]\n\n**Output:** [2,2]\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nThere are two queries.\n\nFirst query: `big_nums[2..5] = [1,2,4,1]`. The product of them is 8. The result is `8 % 3 = 2`.\n\nSecond query: `big_nums[7] = 2`. The result is `2 % 4 = 2`.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= queries.length <= 500`\n\n- `queries[i].length == 3`\n\n- `0 <= queries[i][0] <= queries[i][1] <= 10¹⁵`\n\n- `1 <= queries[i][2] <= 10⁵`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/find-products-of-elements-of-big-array/","problemName":"Find Products of Elements of Big Array","problemNumber":3145,"problemSlug":"find-products-of-elements-of-big-array","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":3145,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Hash Table","String"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"You are given two strings `s` and `t` such that every character occurs at most once in `s` and `t` is a permutation of `s`.\n\nThe **permutation difference** between `s` and `t` is defined as the **sum** of the absolute difference between the index of the occurrence of each character in `s` and the index of the occurrence of the same character in `t`.\n\nReturn the **permutation difference** between `s` and `t`.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n**Input:** s = \"abc\", t = \"bac\"\n\n**Output:** 2\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nFor `s = \"abc\"` and `t = \"bac\"`, the permutation difference of `s` and `t` is equal to the sum of:\n\n- The absolute difference between the index of the occurrence of `\"a\"` in `s` and the index of the occurrence of `\"a\"` in `t`.\n\n- The absolute difference between the index of the occurrence of `\"b\"` in `s` and the index of the occurrence of `\"b\"` in `t`.\n\n- The absolute difference between the index of the occurrence of `\"c\"` in `s` and the index of the occurrence of `\"c\"` in `t`.\n\nThat is, the permutation difference between `s` and `t` is equal to `|0 - 1| + |1 - 0| + |2 - 2| = 2`.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n**Input:** s = \"abcde\", t = \"edbac\"\n\n**Output:** 12\n\n**Explanation:** The permutation difference between `s` and `t` is equal to `|0 - 3| + |1 - 2| + |2 - 4| + |3 - 1| + |4 - 0| = 12`.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= s.length <= 26`\n\n- Each character occurs at most once in `s`.\n\n- `t` is a permutation of `s`.\n\n- `s` consists only of lowercase English letters.","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Hash Table","String"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Easy","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":